'''Jean-Pierre-Paul Adam''' was a late 18th and early 19th century [[France|French]] actor.
Born in [[Rouen]], he arrived in [[Ghent]] in 1782 and there played tragic and comic leads in Casimir's company, before becoming co-director of the company with Casimir and Dorgeville in 1784. The following year and several other actors in Ghent were taken on in Brussels, where he and [[Herman Bultos]] headed the [[La Monnaie|Théâtre de la Monnaie]] from 1791 to 1793, with Adam all the while continuing to play lead rôles. During the troubles that followed the [[Brabant Revolution]] (1787–90), Adam and his wife took refuge in [[The Hague]], where they (like Herman Bultos) took ship for [[Hamburg]]. Adam later returned to France, acting at Paris's [[Théâtre de la Gaîté (boulevard du Temple)|Théâtre de la Gaîté]] in 1810 and the [[Théâtre de l'Ambigu-Comique|Ambigu-Comique]] (1811–16).
== References == <references/> * Jacques Isnardon, ''Le théatre de la Monnaie depuis sa fondation jusqu'à nos jours''. Schott Frères. Brussel. 1890.
