{{Infobox CanadianMP | honorific-prefix = | name =John Aldag | honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|MP]] | image = MPjohnAldag.jpg | imagesize = 200px | riding = [[Cloverdale—Langley City]] | parliament = Canadian | term_start =October 19, 2015 | term_end = | predecessor =''Riding established'' | successor = | birth_date =1963 | birth_place =[[Gull Lake, Saskatchewan]] | death_date = | death_place = | profession =Public servant, politician | alma_mater= | party = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] | residence = Langley, British Columbia | footnotes = | spouse =Elaine St. John |}} '''John Aldag''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|MP}} (born 1963) is a Canadian [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] politician, who was elected to represent the [[electoral district (Canada)|riding]] of [[Cloverdale—Langley City]] in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] in the [[Canadian federal election, 2015|2015 federal election]].<ref name="langleytimes.com">[http://www.langleytimes.com/news/334451051.html Election 2015: Aldag claims new riding for Liberals], ''The Langley Times'', October 20, 2015.</ref>
==Early life and career== Aldag was born in rural [[Saskatchewan]]. He earned an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] from [[Royal Roads|Royal Roads University]] and had a 32-year career with [[Parks Canada]], including postings in [[Whitehorse, Yukon|Whitehorse]], [[Lake Louise, Alberta|Lake Louise]], [[Yoho National Park|Yoho]], [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]] and [[Langley, British Columbia (district municipality)|Langley]], where he was the administrator of [[Fort Langley National Historic Site]] before his entry into politics.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title = New MP, Doc’s daughter spread prairie roots|url = http://www.gulllakeadvance.com/?p=2430|website = www.gulllakeadvance.com|access-date = 2016-01-22|last = Kersey|first = Karen|date = January 9, 2016|publisher = Gull Lake Advance}}</ref> Aldag took an unpaid leave from Parks Canada in December 2013 to begin campaigning for election to office, which he ultimately won with nearly 46% of the vote.<ref name="langleytimes.com"/> He resigned his position upon being confirmed as the elected candidate by Elections Canada on October 26, 2015.
Aldag and his wife, Elaine St. John, a doctor, have two daughters and one son, and had lived in Langley for a decade at the time of his election to the House of Commons.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Aldag puts name forward for Liberals in new federal riding – Langley Times|url = http://www.langleytimes.com/news/263893111.html|website = Langley Times|access-date = 2016-01-22}}</ref>
==Politics== Aldag was elected in the [[Canadian federal election, 2015|2015 election]] as a Member of Parliament for [[Cloverdale—Langley City]]. Upon his election, he was appointed to two parliamentary committees; the Environment and Sustainable Development committee and the Special Joint Committee on Physician-Assisted Dying, an issue in which he consulted extensively with his constituents.<ref name="PAD">{{cite news|last1=Holmes|first1=Tracy|title=Legislators face death head on|url=http://www.peacearchnews.com/news/370960411.html|accessdate=29 March 2016|publisher=Peace Arch News|date=3 March 2016}}</ref> The issue of Physician-Assisted Dying touched him, causing him to be a proponent of families having conversations about their wishes in these situations.<ref name="PAD"/> He was later named as well to the House of Commons [[Canadian House of Commons Special Committee on Electoral Reform|Special Committee on Electoral Reform]].
