{{Redirect|Robert Munn|the Australian rules footballer|Bob Munn|the American rower|Robert Munn (rower)}} '''Robert Stewart Munn''' (August 23, 1829 &ndash; December 17, 1894) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]]-born merchant and politician in [[Colony of Newfoundland|Newfoundland]]. He represented Harbour Grace in the [[Newfoundland House of Assembly]] as a [[Conservative parties in Newfoundland (pre-Confederation)|Reform Party]] member from 1889 until his death in 1894.<ref name=cdob/>
The son of Dugald Munn, a banker, and Elizabeth Stewart, he was born in [[County of Bute|Bute]] and came to Newfoundland in 1851 to join the firm of Punton and Munn, which was then owned by his uncle [[John Munn (Newfoundland politician)|John Munn]]. In 1862, Munn became manager of the firm's operation in [[Harbour Grace, Newfoundland and Labrador|Harbour Grace]]. In the same year, he married Elizabeth Munden. In 1872, Munn and his cousin William Punton Munn became partners in the business, now known as John Munn and Company. When William went to England due to poor health in 1881, Munn became the sole manager.<ref name=cdob/>
He was elected to the Newfoundland assembly in 1889 and reelected in 1893.<ref name=cdob/>
A decline in the price of fish had resulted in accumulating debt for John Munn and Company during the 1890s. The Union Bank in St. John's, which held most of that debt, failed in 1894.<ref name=cdob/>
Munn died of [[pleurisy]] in Harbour Grace at the age of 65. His estate was declared insolvent and the company went bankrupt soon afterwards.<ref name=cdob>{{cite DCB |url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/munn_robert_stewart_12E.html |name=Munn, Robert Steward |volume=12 |last=Cuff |first=Robert H. |last2=Kenney |first2=Paul F.}}</ref>
